Crossposted-To: comp.os.linux.help,comp.periphs.scsi
From: pcg@aber.ac.uk (Piercarlo Grandi)
Subject: Re: NEC SCSI CDR-84 CD-ROM no
Reply-To: pcg@aber.ac.uk (Piercarlo Grandi)
Date: Sun, 24 Oct 1993 21:25:48 GMT

>>> On 24 Oct 1993 07:49:18 -0700, mahmha@crl.com (Mark A. Horton) said:

AD> My Linux system doesn't recognize my NEC CDR-84 SCSI CD-ROM
AD> drive. At boot, I see my Adaptec 1542 accessing the drive (LED
AD> flashing), also when Linux tests for SCSI devices, the drive is
AD> accessed but not recognized.

Mark> Francois Vigneron (francois.vigneron@cld9.com) wrote:

Vigneron> I use a NEC CDR-84 CDROM Driver on my Anonymous UUCP site. I
Vigneron> have had enormous problems with it. The answer is to use this
Vigneron> drive as the last device on the SCSI chain and to disable
Vigneron> "sync mode" + "Parity" mode on the Adaptec controler.

Mark> Interesting, I have been running 6 scsi devices off of one HA1542b
Mark> with no problems although I am installing a second HA1542b for
Mark> performance reasons.

Well, I am getting a CDR-74 tomorrow, so I have kept an eye open for
74/84 related articles. I think this gives the scoop:

>>> From: jjctc@lhdsy1.lahabra.chevron.com (James C. Tsiao)
>>> Date: 22 Oct 93 16:58:32 GMT

jjctc> [ ... ] I wrote in article <14226@lhdsy1.lahabra.chevron.com>:

  jjctc> Is anyone able to play a music CD in a NEC MultiSpin 74?
  jjctc> Neither workman nor CDPlayer work for me.  Workman reports
  jjctc> no CD present.  I can mount iso9660 data CDs fine.
  jjctc> ...
  jjctc> I have a NEC 74 hooked up to an Adaptec 1542C.  The Adaptec
  jjctc> recognizes the CD-ROM, but I can only boot Linux if I set
  jjctc> the dip switch in the back for SCSI-1.

jjctc> Thanks for all the responses.  Here are some highlights:

jjctc> - It doesn't work because NEC does not implement the SCSI
jjctc> command mode-select and/or has proprietary ioctl calls.

jjctc> - Try adding the following line to scsi.c in the blacklist
jjctc> structure initializer (around line 118):

jjctc> {"NEC","CD-ROM DRIVE:841","1.0"},  /* Locks-up when LUN>0 polled. */

jjctc> to allow the NEC 74 to boot up in SCSI-2.  This supposedly
jjctc> won't help the audio CD problem though.

jjctc> - Set the NEC 74 to SCSI-2, boot Linux until it locks, turn off
jjctc> then on the NEC, and workman is reported to work after that. [
jjctc> ... ]

Mark> I did have to configure the HA as suggested and set the CDR-84s to
Mark> SCSI-1,

The above message seems to provide some light on the subject. I would
rather avoid disabling parity on the bus... It leaves unprotected the
most crucial link in your machine, and given that the SCSI bus can have
electrical noise on it... It should not, and parity is really minimal
protection, yet!

BTW, I am afraid I once read that up to some ROM release, the Nec 74/84
has the rather dubious quality of not doing disconnect/reconnect, thus
holding the SCSI bus for possibly long periods of time.

Has anbyody got any info on this subject? Has by any chance NEC improved
their SCSI implementation in some recent firmware release?

